WEBVTT

00:17.184 --> 00:20.187
[ambient nature sounds]

00:32.866 --> 00:35.827
[serene music]

00:35.869 --> 00:42.876
♪ ♪

00:49.550 --> 00:52.553
[bird squawking]

01:10.904 --> 01:13.907
[bird squawking]

01:28.797 --> 01:31.800
[birds squawking]

01:34.261 --> 01:37.389
- [blowing softly]

01:41.810 --> 01:44.771
[blows]

01:48.025 --> 01:50.068
There's a bunch of 'em
on this bird.

01:50.110 --> 01:52.738
Several of 'em right here
on the top of the head.

01:56.366 --> 02:00.120
There's another one
just loose.

02:00.162 --> 02:02.122
And just dropped.

02:02.164 --> 02:03.373
[chuckles]

02:03.415 --> 02:05.751
We may not see that one again.

02:05.792 --> 02:07.461
This is really quite unusual.

02:07.503 --> 02:08.628
Two of 'em just fell off here.

02:08.669 --> 02:10.589
They're all apparently
completely engorged,

02:10.631 --> 02:12.799
and ready just to fall off.

02:15.844 --> 02:18.889
[music builds]

02:47.918 --> 02:51.713
- Here's one.
Here's one.

02:51.755 --> 02:53.715
Here.

02:53.757 --> 02:55.091
Here. Here.

02:57.469 --> 03:01.682
So that's 81 larvae
in one 30-meter drag.

03:04.518 --> 03:05.602
- We have this project

03:05.644 --> 03:07.062
where we're testing ticks

03:07.104 --> 03:09.064
from all over the country.

03:09.940 --> 03:12.401
These are ticks that are coming
into contact with people.

03:13.318 --> 03:14.945
- Texas, New York,

03:14.987 --> 03:18.323
Virginia, Florida,
Pennsylvania, Missouri,

03:18.365 --> 03:20.826
Oklahoma, Wyoming, California,

03:20.868 --> 03:23.912
Georgia, Ohio,
Indiana, Nevada,

03:23.954 --> 03:26.415
Alabama, North Carolina.

03:29.668 --> 03:32.004
- Ticks are not just
in the Northeast,

03:32.045 --> 03:34.339
where we classically
think they are.

03:34.381 --> 03:36.508
They're in the South.
They're in the far West.

03:36.550 --> 03:38.552
And that means that
these things are everywhere.

03:38.594 --> 03:41.555
[suspenseful music]

03:41.597 --> 03:44.391
♪ ♪

03:44.433 --> 03:45.642
- There is an epidemic

03:45.684 --> 03:47.102
disease spreading across

03:47.144 --> 03:49.021
the United States.

03:49.062 --> 03:51.190
It's called Lyme disease.

03:51.231 --> 03:52.733
It's serious and can be fatal.

03:54.317 --> 03:56.445
- As it digs in
for a meal of blood,

03:56.486 --> 03:58.238
it can inject
the germ it carries

03:58.280 --> 04:00.490
right into your bloodstream.

04:00.532 --> 04:04.036
Shaped like a corkscrew
and called a spirochete,

04:04.077 --> 04:06.872
first cousin of the spirochete
that causes syphilis,

04:06.914 --> 04:08.624
and equally elusive.

04:10.584 --> 04:13.170
- The disease causes symptoms
that look like dementia,

04:13.212 --> 04:14.630
Alzheimer's disease,

04:14.671 --> 04:17.173
multiple sclerosis, ALS.

04:18.634 --> 04:20.844
- Meanwhile, debate is growing
over the proper treatment

04:20.886 --> 04:22.346
for Lyme disease.

04:22.387 --> 04:23.847
all: Lyme is spreading!

04:23.889 --> 04:25.390
- Most cases respond

04:25.432 --> 04:27.059
to treatment with antibiotics,

04:27.100 --> 04:28.852
but others do not.

04:28.894 --> 04:31.522
Whether they suffer from
a chronic form of the disease

04:31.563 --> 04:33.941
is a hotly contested debate
among doctors,

04:33.982 --> 04:35.901
patients,
and insurance companies.

04:37.444 --> 04:40.322
- There is a public perception
that Lyme disease

04:40.364 --> 04:43.534
can routinely present
in a myriad of ways.

04:43.575 --> 04:44.909
That is incorrect.

04:44.952 --> 04:46.870
- Right now,
my hands are burning.

04:46.912 --> 04:47.913
My feet are burning.

04:47.955 --> 04:49.623
Every joint in my body

04:49.665 --> 04:51.250
hurts all day.

04:51.291 --> 04:53.126
That's Lyme disease.

04:53.168 --> 04:56.088
- You brought a tick.

04:56.129 --> 04:59.633
- The Lyme disease, the ticks,
they're everywhere.

04:59.675 --> 05:02.553
- Last year, there were cases
reported in 24 states.

05:02.594 --> 05:04.930
- 37 states.
- 43 states.

05:04.972 --> 05:06.598
- 45 states.

05:06.640 --> 05:08.851
- And it may be as close
as your backyard.

05:08.892 --> 05:11.854
[suspenseful music]

05:11.895 --> 05:18.902
♪ ♪

05:27.828 --> 05:30.831
[ambient noises]

06:05.657 --> 06:07.242
- [sighs]

06:09.786 --> 06:12.998
I get a really guilty feeling
when I come down here.

06:16.710 --> 06:18.795
Because, uh, you know,

06:18.837 --> 06:20.631
I guess it's
about starting something

06:20.672 --> 06:22.925
that I was never able
to finish.

06:25.010 --> 06:27.387
And it kind of just reminds me

06:27.429 --> 06:29.890
of when life used
to be normal.

06:29.932 --> 06:32.893
[soft dramatic music]

06:32.935 --> 06:34.311
♪ ♪

06:34.353 --> 06:37.606
It's really hard to make people
understand what's at stake.

06:39.441 --> 06:42.611
It's so much more than
just suffering and disease.

06:42.653 --> 06:45.656
[kids vocalizing]

06:48.116 --> 06:52.329
It's like an atomic bomb
drops down on your life

06:52.371 --> 06:56.667
and just turns everything
upside down.

06:57.835 --> 07:00.045
Tons of medications.

07:00.087 --> 07:01.839
These are pill organizers.

07:02.714 --> 07:04.466
Oxygen.

07:06.385 --> 07:08.512
Empty meds.

07:08.554 --> 07:10.931
Those are all full.

07:10.973 --> 07:13.225
This is what life became.

07:13.267 --> 07:15.936
I--I would let it all burn

07:15.978 --> 07:18.397
just to see Julia walk.

07:18.438 --> 07:21.149
Let's see you go. Do it.
Let's see you go.

07:22.734 --> 07:25.070
- As a kid, I was very eager.

07:26.363 --> 07:28.073
I was very active.

07:28.115 --> 07:29.616
I loved to dance.

07:31.076 --> 07:33.412
And I used to love
to ride my bike.

07:33.453 --> 07:36.206
- Feeling good?
- Fine.

07:36.248 --> 07:38.584
But those things about me
started to change.

07:39.960 --> 07:42.254
Even though I knew
something was wrong,

07:42.296 --> 07:44.506
I never imagined
it would be this.

07:54.975 --> 07:57.269
Like a week before I started

07:57.311 --> 07:59.855
to get seriously ill,

07:59.897 --> 08:01.857
well, I started
to notice it was hard

08:01.899 --> 08:03.650
to get out of bed
in the morning.

08:03.692 --> 08:05.235
And you know,
everybody has those days

08:05.277 --> 08:07.487
where they can't imagine
waking up.

08:07.529 --> 08:10.449
But it was every day,
and it took me, like,

08:10.490 --> 08:11.950
an hour to get out of bed.

08:13.243 --> 08:15.913
The second week
that I was sick,

08:15.954 --> 08:17.956
I was just sitting in class,

08:17.998 --> 08:20.459
and my legs went numb.

08:20.501 --> 08:21.752
- The school called me,
and they said,

08:21.793 --> 08:23.462
"Something is seriously wrong
with Julia.

08:23.504 --> 08:25.589
You need to get here
right away."

08:25.631 --> 08:26.632
When I got there,

08:26.673 --> 08:29.259
I found Julia
in the nurse's office,

08:29.301 --> 08:31.470
and she was just lifeless

08:31.512 --> 08:32.888
across two chairs.

08:32.929 --> 08:35.599
And I went to go nudge Julia,
and I'm like, "Julia. Julia.

08:35.640 --> 08:37.058
What's the matter?
What happened?"

08:37.100 --> 08:38.684
She's like,
"Dad, I can't see."

08:38.727 --> 08:40.854
And she said,
"I can't feel my arms,

08:40.895 --> 08:43.065
and I can't feel my legs."

08:43.106 --> 08:45.150
So I took her straight
to the hospital.

08:47.778 --> 08:50.489
Julia was tested
for everything several times,

08:50.531 --> 08:54.409
not just once, and everything
comes back negative.

08:54.451 --> 08:57.120
It was a very confusing time.

08:57.162 --> 08:59.373
I felt like Julia was dying.

08:59.414 --> 09:03.210
So I spent a lot of time
researching all her symptoms.

09:03.252 --> 09:05.212
Julia's doctor would come
to me and say,

09:05.254 --> 09:07.756
"Did you find anything else
that we could test for?"

09:07.798 --> 09:09.341
So I would give her a list,

09:09.383 --> 09:12.553
and she would run tests
for everything I gave her.

09:12.594 --> 09:14.888
Again, I put in the search
with Julia's symptoms,

09:14.930 --> 09:17.558
and Lyme disease comes up.

09:17.599 --> 09:20.185
And I said,
"I have to read this."

09:20.227 --> 09:22.271
And then I started
researching the area

09:22.312 --> 09:24.439
that we vacationed in,

09:24.481 --> 09:27.192
the area around our house.

09:27.234 --> 09:29.444
There's Lyme disease
in these areas.

09:30.445 --> 09:32.739
The story is told very clearly

09:32.781 --> 09:35.325
just looking
at her medical records.

09:35.367 --> 09:36.827
You know,
Julia got bit by a tick

09:36.869 --> 09:38.912
when she was nine years old.

09:38.954 --> 09:43.458
She went undiagnosed
for the next two years.

09:43.500 --> 09:44.960
I felt like somebody
threw a bucket

09:45.002 --> 09:46.920
of ice water over my head.

09:46.962 --> 09:49.923
I called Josephine.
I called the kids.

09:49.965 --> 09:51.383
I--I tell them,
"I know what she's got.

09:51.425 --> 09:52.968
She's got Lyme."

09:53.010 --> 09:56.638
And when the doctor came in,
it was like night and day.

09:56.680 --> 09:59.766
She went from being this
wonderful, supporting doctor,

09:59.808 --> 10:01.185
willing to try anything,

10:01.226 --> 10:04.897
to adamant, "No, impossible.
This is not it."

10:04.938 --> 10:07.900
[inquisitive music]

10:07.941 --> 10:09.067
♪ ♪

10:09.109 --> 10:12.738
I mean, it was almost like
as if we were using profanity,

10:12.779 --> 10:14.990
like "Lyme disease"
was a bad word.

10:16.366 --> 10:19.828
They saw nothing wrong
in the laboratory test,

10:19.870 --> 10:22.372
and they figured
she must be faking it.

10:24.166 --> 10:26.960
- I remember just hearing that
and, like,

10:27.002 --> 10:28.378
I--I couldn't believe it.

10:28.420 --> 10:31.632
Like, I'm having
real symptoms.

10:31.673 --> 10:34.551
I was comatose.
I was losing my hair.

10:34.593 --> 10:36.512
- Fever, flaccid paralysis.

10:36.553 --> 10:38.931
How could she be faking fever?

10:38.972 --> 10:41.892
The color blue.
She was blue in color.

10:43.769 --> 10:47.439
The doctor insisted that this
had to be conversion syndrome.

10:51.485 --> 10:53.612
I felt like we were
being attacked.

10:53.654 --> 10:56.990
And I felt like I had to start
recording what was going on.

11:46.456 --> 11:47.833
- [sniffles]

11:47.875 --> 11:50.335
She was only 11 years old.

11:50.377 --> 11:52.629
You know, and she had a--

11:52.671 --> 11:54.506
she had to put up
an argument like that.

11:55.632 --> 11:57.676
The first thing I think of is,

11:57.718 --> 12:00.846
how many people
go through this

12:00.888 --> 12:02.806
and then just go home
and suffer in silence?

12:06.059 --> 12:09.062
[birds singing]

12:33.378 --> 12:37.883
- I came to the Lyme disease
controversy as an outsider,

12:37.925 --> 12:39.593
as an investigative reporter

12:39.635 --> 12:40.761
who wanted to find out

12:40.802 --> 12:42.179
what was going on.

12:43.180 --> 12:45.057
I went into it intending

12:45.098 --> 12:48.060
to look at the trend
in Lyme disease cases.

12:48.977 --> 12:52.689
Was government doing enough
to control ticks?

12:52.731 --> 12:55.817
I also wanted to know
why I could get a vaccine

12:55.859 --> 12:58.070
for my dog but there was none

12:58.111 --> 13:00.280
for my children
and grandchildren.

13:00.322 --> 13:03.283
[tense music]

13:03.325 --> 13:04.326
♪ ♪

13:04.368 --> 13:08.997
The main question is whether
Lyme disease is chronic.

13:09.039 --> 13:12.125
Does it respond
to the short courses

13:12.167 --> 13:14.545
of antibiotics
that are recommended?

13:16.421 --> 13:18.841
By and large, a small group

13:18.882 --> 13:22.052
of researchers
and government officials

13:22.094 --> 13:26.598
basically say short courses
of antibiotics cure.

13:30.018 --> 13:32.479
There was another side,
though.

13:32.521 --> 13:35.482
I found patients who had been

13:35.524 --> 13:38.735
to 10, 15, 20 doctors,

13:38.777 --> 13:43.532
and they still had lingering,
serious symptoms,

13:43.574 --> 13:46.994
and were tired
of being ignored.

13:49.413 --> 13:53.125
What I found
after two or three stories

13:53.165 --> 13:58.463
was that I had waded into one
of the most controversial,

13:58.505 --> 14:04.636
divisive, and vicious medical
debates in medicine today.

14:05.804 --> 14:08.765
[sweeping music]

14:08.807 --> 14:12.895
♪ ♪

14:12.936 --> 14:15.355
- There is a medical detection
story in the making.

14:15.397 --> 14:18.066
It deals with arthritis
and the possibility

14:18.108 --> 14:20.861
that a type of arthritis
may have been uncovered

14:20.903 --> 14:23.488
which is caused
by an insect bite.

14:24.573 --> 14:26.241
The outbreak
of arthritis is centered

14:26.283 --> 14:28.368
in Lyme, Connecticut,
a small town located

14:28.410 --> 14:30.162
on the Connecticut River.

14:30.204 --> 14:32.289
In the past three years,
there have been 51

14:32.331 --> 14:34.750
reported cases
of the mysterious arthritis.

14:34.790 --> 14:36.877
Several adults
have been treated,

14:36.919 --> 14:39.671
but most of the victims
are children.

14:39.713 --> 14:42.007
- So in the early 1970s,

14:42.049 --> 14:45.385
Allen Steere is
a newly minted rheumatologist

14:45.427 --> 14:48.931
who has also studied
epidemiology, namely,

14:48.972 --> 14:52.518
"How do we define
and count diseases?"

14:52.559 --> 14:54.436
He's the guy from Yale

14:54.478 --> 14:57.648
who answers the call
of a young mother

14:57.689 --> 14:59.983
who reports that two
of her children

15:00.025 --> 15:03.403
have been diagnosed
with juvenile arthritis,

15:03.445 --> 15:05.280
as have a number of others.

15:06.240 --> 15:08.700
- Let me ask you, Dr. Steere,
how did you get on the trail

15:08.742 --> 15:11.495
of this particular form
of arthritis?

15:11.537 --> 15:14.414
- Frank, a number of parents
in this community

15:14.456 --> 15:16.625
were concerned
that so many children

15:16.667 --> 15:18.627
seemed to have arthritis.

15:18.669 --> 15:21.880
This is where the medical
detective story comes in.

15:21.922 --> 15:24.716
Actually, like a detective,

15:24.758 --> 15:27.511
you try to determine
where the people were

15:27.553 --> 15:30.889
when they got their illness,
when it occurred,

15:30.931 --> 15:33.016
where they were
in relation to one another.

15:34.518 --> 15:37.813
- In 1977,
he publishes a paper

15:37.855 --> 15:41.066
on an epidemic of arthritis.

15:41.108 --> 15:43.986
Dr. Steere found that 25%

15:44.027 --> 15:47.614
of that original Lyme disease group
had something of a rash,

15:47.656 --> 15:50.117
a bull's-eye rash.

15:50.158 --> 15:53.245
And he also links this illness

15:53.287 --> 15:55.247
to the bite of a tick.

15:56.373 --> 16:00.002
But as time went on,
his focus changed,

16:00.043 --> 16:04.673
and Dr. Steere was recognized
in the Lyme community

16:04.715 --> 16:07.384
as someone
who was not their ally.

16:07.426 --> 16:10.721
all: Lyme is spreading!
Lyme is spreading!

16:10.762 --> 16:14.474
- All we want
is long-term treatment.

16:15.684 --> 16:18.437
- If a patient thinks
that they have Lyme disease,

16:18.478 --> 16:20.439
are being treated
with antibiotic therapy,

16:20.480 --> 16:24.568
and are not responding,
the most common reason

16:24.610 --> 16:26.612
is that they actually have
another illness.

16:26.653 --> 16:29.489
[soft dramatic music]

16:29.531 --> 16:31.950
- As Lyme disease evolved,

16:31.992 --> 16:34.328
doctors needed guidance.

16:34.369 --> 16:36.580
So a group got together,

16:36.622 --> 16:40.209
called the Infectious Diseases
Society of America,

16:40.250 --> 16:43.962
and wrote the first guidelines
to treat Lyme disease,

16:44.004 --> 16:46.340
where they staked their claim

16:46.381 --> 16:49.301
that this disease
was not chronic.

16:49.343 --> 16:52.095
♪ ♪

16:52.137 --> 16:55.098
- This is a fairly benign
disease if treated early.

16:55.140 --> 16:57.851
- It has, on occasion,
been life-disruptive,

16:57.893 --> 17:00.479
but I don't want
to overemphasize that fact.

17:01.980 --> 17:05.150
- As hard as the IDSA tried

17:05.192 --> 17:08.904
to solidify treatment
of Lyme disease

17:08.945 --> 17:11.198
in one way only,

17:11.240 --> 17:14.660
there were cracks
that emerged over time.

17:14.701 --> 17:17.162
And these cracks, if you will,

17:17.204 --> 17:20.999
were, you know, a doctor here,
a doctor there,

17:21.040 --> 17:22.166
who discovered

17:22.209 --> 17:25.212
following the guidelines
didn't always work.

17:25.253 --> 17:27.756
[tense music]

17:27.798 --> 17:31.009
- I decided to return
to Westchester County

17:31.051 --> 17:33.846
around 1985.

17:33.887 --> 17:36.598
Unbeknownst to me,
Westchester at that time

17:36.640 --> 17:40.477
was beginning
to be a burgeoning epidemic.

17:40.519 --> 17:41.770
I knew virtually nothing

17:41.812 --> 17:42.938
about Lyme disease

17:42.980 --> 17:44.273
when I went into practice.

17:44.314 --> 17:46.733
I knew the name. That's about it.

17:46.775 --> 17:50.153
What I was observing was,
like, incredible.

17:50.195 --> 17:52.030
People get sick.
You treat them.

17:52.072 --> 17:53.448
They get better.

17:53.490 --> 17:56.743
And then the same symptoms
would start creeping back.

17:56.785 --> 18:00.289
How can a organism survive
these antibiotics?

18:00.330 --> 18:02.165
[phone ringing]

18:02.207 --> 18:03.876
- These were really
in the early days,

18:03.917 --> 18:06.253
when we were all looking
for answers.

18:06.295 --> 18:07.546
I was having a lot of patients

18:07.588 --> 18:08.881
coming into my office

18:08.922 --> 18:10.257
with bull's-eye rashes,

18:10.299 --> 18:13.343
and about 80% would get better
with standard antibiotics,

18:13.385 --> 18:15.804
but 20% would not.

18:15.846 --> 18:17.264
So I would look
at the guidelines,

18:17.306 --> 18:19.516
but unfortunately,
those guidelines were not

18:19.558 --> 18:21.560
specific enough
to deal with the complexity

18:21.602 --> 18:22.603
of what I was seeing.

18:24.438 --> 18:26.648
- So when I first was learning
about Lyme disease,

18:26.690 --> 18:28.734
I was really interested
in an article

18:28.775 --> 18:30.152
that came out in 1989

18:30.194 --> 18:32.321
written by a neurologist,
Andrew Pachner.

18:32.362 --> 18:35.324
His article was called
"Lyme disease, the New 'Great Imitator.'"

18:35.365 --> 18:37.951
And in that article,
he presented six cases

18:37.993 --> 18:39.369
that were fascinating.

18:39.411 --> 18:41.038
There was one case
of an individual

18:41.079 --> 18:42.497
who had aggression outbursts.

18:42.539 --> 18:45.083
A young child, and when he was
treated, the OCD went away.

18:45.125 --> 18:47.211
Here we have
an infectious illness

18:47.252 --> 18:49.046
that's causing
psychiatric problems.

18:49.087 --> 18:51.006
So why was Lyme disease

18:51.048 --> 18:52.424
called
"the new great imitator?"

18:52.466 --> 18:55.135
Because the first
great imitator was syphilis.

18:55.177 --> 18:57.804
Syphilis was caused
by a spiral-shaped organism

18:57.846 --> 18:59.223
called a treponeme,

18:59.264 --> 19:02.935
and Lyme disease is caused
by a spiral-shaped organism.

19:02.976 --> 19:06.438
Syphilis caused a huge variety
of manifestations.

19:06.480 --> 19:09.024
So it mimicked other diseases.

19:09.066 --> 19:11.151
- Lyme disease may
be the great masquerader

19:11.193 --> 19:12.986
of the 1980s and '90s

19:13.028 --> 19:14.696
in that it can do
almost anything.

19:17.157 --> 19:20.118
- The Lyme disease spirochete
is shaped like a corkscrew,

19:20.160 --> 19:23.830
so it drills
through your joint cartilage.

19:24.957 --> 19:27.459
It quickly leaves
the bloodstream.

19:27.501 --> 19:29.378
It goes to organs.

19:29.419 --> 19:32.047
It goes to the heart
and the brain.

19:33.715 --> 19:36.051
- The Lyme disease bacteria,
Borrelia burgdorferi,

19:36.093 --> 19:37.803
is definitely one
of the smartest bacteria

19:37.845 --> 19:39.847
on the planet.

19:39.888 --> 19:42.182
This organism knows
how to change forms.

19:43.642 --> 19:46.186
It knows how to hide.

19:46.228 --> 19:48.313
And the way it evades
the immune system--

19:48.355 --> 19:51.817
Lyme is more difficult
to find on the blood tests.

19:51.859 --> 19:54.736
- And many of us clinicians
were observing that.

19:54.778 --> 19:58.073
Patients that we strongly
believed had Lyme disease,

19:58.115 --> 20:01.076
their standard tests
for Lyme disease were negative.

20:01.118 --> 20:04.246
And as a result, it is easy
for people to honestly,

20:04.288 --> 20:07.165
you know, confuse Lyme
for other conditions.

20:07.207 --> 20:09.793
- The most common misdiagnoses
that I see in my practice

20:09.835 --> 20:12.754
are people who've been diagnosed
with chronic fatigue syndrome,

20:12.796 --> 20:16.049
fibromyalgia,
rheumatoid arthritis, lupus,

20:16.091 --> 20:17.885
multiple sclerosis
is a big one,

20:17.926 --> 20:20.220
patients who have dementia,
Alzheimer's.

20:20.262 --> 20:22.973
Lyme can imitate
all of these different diseases.

20:23.015 --> 20:26.268
So it's a very,
very complex organism,

20:26.310 --> 20:28.478
and you really have
to understand the biology

20:28.520 --> 20:30.939
to understand how to treat
these patients effectively.

20:32.858 --> 20:35.986
- We're now up
to almost 500,000 cases

20:36.028 --> 20:38.739
of Lyme disease
in America every year.

20:39.823 --> 20:41.950
There are more cases
of Lyme disease

20:41.992 --> 20:44.953
than HIV
and breast cancer combined.

20:46.121 --> 20:48.624
Of those 500,000,

20:48.665 --> 20:52.711
about 10% to 20% will stay sick

20:52.753 --> 20:55.214
for some period of time.

20:55.255 --> 20:57.508
We now believe
that something on the order

20:57.549 --> 20:59.134
of 2 million people

20:59.176 --> 21:02.471
suffer the aftereffects
of Lyme disease

21:02.513 --> 21:03.764
in the United States.

21:05.224 --> 21:08.685
So 50 years later,
here we are,

21:08.727 --> 21:11.396
and we still haven't
answered many

21:11.438 --> 21:14.858
of the most urgent
and basic questions.

21:15.901 --> 21:19.571
"Chronic Lyme disease"
is a rejected term

21:19.613 --> 21:22.199
in American medicine.

21:22.241 --> 21:25.452
The question is, why?

21:25.494 --> 21:28.497
[ambient nature sounds]

21:34.586 --> 21:38.131
- Home, sweet home
away from home.

21:38.173 --> 21:42.511
And it is...

21:42.553 --> 21:46.348
time to do the ritual ironing.

21:59.820 --> 22:02.739
I feel a little guilty
staying in this place.

22:02.781 --> 22:05.701
Usually, like,
an Embassy Suites person.

22:08.745 --> 22:11.498
I literally just came
from Carlisle, Pennsylvania,

22:11.540 --> 22:14.960
which is, like,
an incredibly endemic area.

22:15.002 --> 22:18.463
And just
to hear the stories there,

22:18.505 --> 22:21.383
with whole towns
and neighborhoods being infected.

22:22.843 --> 22:27.556
The mere fact
that I validate their disease,

22:27.598 --> 22:30.058
you know, and recognize
it's not all in their head,

22:30.100 --> 22:31.643
that they're not just
fabricating everything--

22:31.685 --> 22:34.146
I think that's so important
for people

22:34.188 --> 22:36.398
to have maybe
somebody like me,

22:36.440 --> 22:39.818
who's in the medical
profession, saying,

22:39.860 --> 22:42.237
"I hear you."
You know, "I get it."

22:43.488 --> 22:46.617
- It is my honor to introduce
tonight's keynote speaker,

22:46.658 --> 22:48.535
Dr. Neil Spector.

22:48.577 --> 22:50.037
Dr. Spector is one of the top

22:50.078 --> 22:52.623
breast cancer scientists
in the country.

22:52.664 --> 22:55.375
The Lyme community
is so incredibly fortunate

22:55.417 --> 22:57.794
to have one of the smartest
minds in research,

22:57.836 --> 22:59.421
who is working
towards better treatment

22:59.463 --> 23:02.007
and a cure
for tick-borne illnesses.

23:05.511 --> 23:07.971
- Okay. Lyme disease.

23:08.013 --> 23:09.348
It's everywhere, right?

23:09.389 --> 23:11.308
This isn't just a problem
in Connecticut,

23:11.350 --> 23:12.935
New York, New Jersey.

23:12.976 --> 23:14.728
It's all over the place.

23:14.770 --> 23:16.522
And it's only getting worse.

23:17.856 --> 23:20.108
We've got people
at the prime of their lives

23:20.150 --> 23:22.402
who are taken out of society,

23:22.444 --> 23:26.865
and yet we have no clue
what's going on with them.

23:28.242 --> 23:32.162
I'm coming up on ten years
of a heart transplant recipient.

23:32.204 --> 23:35.749
That was an evening that I'll
never forget, Friday evening.

23:35.791 --> 23:39.044
Surgeon walked into my room,
and he said to me,

23:39.086 --> 23:41.672
"You'll be dead by Monday
without a heart transplant."

23:41.713 --> 23:44.633
[hopeful music]

23:44.675 --> 23:47.094
You can do all
the right things in the world

23:47.135 --> 23:49.012
and get bit by a tick,

23:49.054 --> 23:51.640
and it'll change
your world forever.

23:52.891 --> 23:55.894
[birds singing]

23:59.565 --> 24:01.775
I'd just moved here
to North Carolina.

24:01.817 --> 24:04.570
It was 1998.

24:04.611 --> 24:06.154
Just started a new job.

24:06.196 --> 24:08.490
Our daughter
was a few weeks old.

24:10.951 --> 24:13.203
I had always been
unbelievably healthy.

24:13.245 --> 24:14.705
I mean, I had ran marathons.

24:14.746 --> 24:18.208
I used to run ten miles a day,
six days a week.

24:18.250 --> 24:20.961
So it was a very foreign
experience for me

24:21.003 --> 24:24.047
to go from taking care
of cancer patients

24:24.089 --> 24:27.759
to barely being able
to walk ten yards

24:27.801 --> 24:29.553
without having to stop.

24:30.846 --> 24:33.599
We went through
autoimmune diseases, lupus.

24:33.640 --> 24:35.184
All the tests were negative.

24:35.225 --> 24:37.019
I completely fell
through the cracks

24:37.060 --> 24:39.229
of the medical system.

24:39.271 --> 24:41.690
And it wasn't until four years
into my illness

24:41.732 --> 24:43.901
that I developed arthritis.

24:43.942 --> 24:46.069
And so I started
piecing it together and said,

24:46.111 --> 24:48.697
you know, "I'm convinced
I have Lyme disease."

24:51.450 --> 24:53.869
I got a call in my office,

24:53.911 --> 24:56.788
and the cardiologist said
to me,

24:56.830 --> 24:58.790
"Is there a chair nearby?"

25:00.751 --> 25:03.253
You know, "You've got
a severely damaged heart.

25:03.295 --> 25:05.923
You need to be evaluated
for a heart transplant."

25:07.382 --> 25:09.468
I'm not sure
how I drove home.

25:09.510 --> 25:12.471
Just completely in tears,

25:12.513 --> 25:14.306
thinking, "This is it."

25:14.348 --> 25:17.809
Not gonna live
beyond a certain age.

25:17.851 --> 25:19.937
Never gonna see
my daughter grow older.

25:19.978 --> 25:22.689
I'm not gonna see
any of the milestones.

25:24.316 --> 25:27.194
And then I just realized,
you know,

25:27.236 --> 25:30.572
not gonna just roll over
and let that be the answer.

25:31.740 --> 25:33.659
I'm gonna do
whatever it takes.

25:35.786 --> 25:37.746
"Few minutes after
telephone call

25:37.788 --> 25:40.958
that 'your new heart
has been found.'"

25:42.793 --> 25:45.671
Yep.
Giving the old V sign.

25:45.712 --> 25:47.965
- Moment of victory.

25:48.006 --> 25:50.217
[tense music]

25:50.259 --> 25:51.301
♪ ♪

25:51.343 --> 25:53.428
But then you sit
with all those other feelings

25:53.470 --> 25:56.974
of the person
who lost their life.

25:57.015 --> 25:59.226
That's a whole other side
of things too,

25:59.268 --> 26:04.731
the sitting with "What is
their family going through?"

26:04.773 --> 26:07.943
Those were hard emotions
to sort out.

26:07.985 --> 26:10.487
- They were, yeah.
They're still difficult.

26:10.529 --> 26:12.573
- They are still difficult.

26:15.826 --> 26:18.161
- I think about that a lot.

26:18.203 --> 26:20.789
You know, why me?

26:20.831 --> 26:22.541
Sometimes you feel
the pressure

26:22.583 --> 26:23.917
of having to live your life

26:23.959 --> 26:26.211
in an extraordinary way
for those people

26:26.253 --> 26:29.464
who unfortunately
didn't have the opportunity.

26:31.091 --> 26:33.927
You know, with all these unknowns,
there is one known,

26:33.969 --> 26:36.096
and that's that people
are falling through the cracks

26:36.138 --> 26:37.556
of the medical system.

26:37.598 --> 26:39.892
The burden should not be
on people who are sick

26:39.933 --> 26:41.935
to prove that they're sick.

26:41.977 --> 26:46.356
It should be on us,
as medical professionals,

26:46.398 --> 26:50.235
to better understand what's
going on and to help them.

26:55.824 --> 26:58.827
[TV drones in background]

27:11.215 --> 27:14.343
- It was a very hard time
for all of us.

27:14.384 --> 27:17.012
We felt we were losing Julia.

27:18.263 --> 27:21.517
I had nobody
to take care of Julia.

27:21.558 --> 27:24.478
[soft dramatic music]

27:24.520 --> 27:27.731
So me and my wife
had to make a decision.

27:27.773 --> 27:30.192
One of us had to stay home.

27:31.151 --> 27:34.613
- My dad decided that he
wasn't gonna go back to work.

27:34.655 --> 27:36.990
And I remember it
breaking my heart,

27:37.032 --> 27:39.326
because I was
ruining everybody's life,

27:39.368 --> 27:43.497
and I couldn't control it,
couldn't do anything about it.

27:43.539 --> 27:47.543
- We were struggling.
I was without salary.

27:47.584 --> 27:51.046
It felt like
an unwinnable battle.

27:51.088 --> 27:55.175
And then something
really extraordinary happened.

27:55.217 --> 27:57.886
♪ ♪

27:57.928 --> 28:00.889
- This is the plane
that is bringing Pope Francis

28:00.931 --> 28:03.976
here to New York City
for the very first time.

28:04.017 --> 28:05.894
Tremendous sense
of excitement.

28:05.936 --> 28:07.604
And here he is.

28:07.646 --> 28:09.481
- Holy Father!

28:09.523 --> 28:13.151
- He steps out of the plane,
and it's almost like he makes,

28:13.193 --> 28:15.487
like,
a beeline straight to me.

28:15.529 --> 28:17.698
- Holy Father.

28:17.739 --> 28:19.491
- And, Julia, how come
you're in the wheelchair?

28:19.533 --> 28:21.910
I understand you're fighting
a tough fight, right?

28:21.952 --> 28:24.872
- Well, I've been undiagnosed
for four months,

28:24.913 --> 28:28.000
and I have a clinical diagnosis
of Lyme disease.

28:28.041 --> 28:29.710
- And why did you
come here today?

28:29.751 --> 28:32.212
- I came here 'cause I wanted
to meet the pope,

28:32.254 --> 28:34.548
'cause I believe in a miracle.

28:34.590 --> 28:37.342
- You believe in a miracle.

28:37.384 --> 28:39.845
- She just garnered
a lot of media attention.

28:39.887 --> 28:42.347
We started getting phone calls
from every network.

28:42.389 --> 28:43.765
- This was
the strangest story.

28:43.807 --> 28:46.101
A vibrant,
healthy 12-year-old girl.

28:46.143 --> 28:47.895
- You know, suddenly,
in, like, a second,

28:47.936 --> 28:49.188
my life just changed.

28:49.229 --> 28:50.856
- The mothers at Julia's school,

28:50.898 --> 28:52.608
they started
this GoFundMe page

28:52.649 --> 28:54.568
that was very successful.

28:54.610 --> 28:56.612
- We started getting bombarded
with letters

28:56.653 --> 28:58.614
from all different people
who had Lyme disease

28:58.655 --> 29:00.407
around the world.

29:00.449 --> 29:02.576
- We went from being alone

29:02.618 --> 29:04.995
to being, like, exposed.

29:05.037 --> 29:07.122
And, you know,
we didn't realize it then,

29:07.164 --> 29:10.542
but we were in the middle
of a tremendous controversy.

29:10.584 --> 29:12.669
- Convinced
that Julia had chronic Lyme,

29:12.711 --> 29:14.838
her father decided
to fight back,

29:14.880 --> 29:16.673
only to find himself
right in the middle

29:16.715 --> 29:18.926
of a mind-boggling medical war.

29:18.967 --> 29:20.802
- There's a lot
of misinformation out there

29:20.844 --> 29:22.095
about Lyme disease.

29:22.137 --> 29:23.805
- Wormser was a lead author

29:23.847 --> 29:27.100
of Lyme treatment guidelines
followed by the CDC.

29:27.142 --> 29:28.852
Recently, he equated some

29:28.894 --> 29:31.688
of the chronic Lyme conversation
to fake news.

29:31.730 --> 29:33.273
He never treated Julia,

29:33.315 --> 29:36.235
but he influenced many
who did.

29:36.276 --> 29:39.029
- I'll never forget the day
we got the phone call.

29:39.071 --> 29:42.074
I went outside
to have a cigarette,

29:42.115 --> 29:44.117
and my phone rang.

29:44.159 --> 29:47.371
And I pick up the phone,
and it's somebody from the CDC.

31:08.994 --> 31:10.871
Not too long after that,

31:10.913 --> 31:13.790
Julia was interviewed
by Fox 5,

31:13.832 --> 31:16.585
and I excitedly shared
this information

31:16.627 --> 31:18.504
with a list of my contacts.

31:18.545 --> 31:23.425
Somehow, my email was sent
to Dr. Phillip Baker.

31:23.467 --> 31:26.261
Here's another man
who has never met us.

31:26.303 --> 31:27.930
He has never had
the opportunity

31:27.971 --> 31:30.307
to look
at Julia's medical records.

31:30.349 --> 31:34.102
And he writes, "Since the results
of laboratory tests

31:34.144 --> 31:36.772
"for the diagnosis
of Lyme disease were negative,

31:36.813 --> 31:41.026
"were other possibilities considered
to explain such symptoms?

31:41.068 --> 31:44.112
"If not, wasn't this child
denied the opportunity

31:44.154 --> 31:46.406
"to get the medical treatment
she deserved

31:46.448 --> 31:50.118
"by obsessively focusing
on Lyme disease?

31:50.160 --> 31:52.371
"Perhaps this is
the most tragic outcome

31:52.412 --> 31:54.414
of this sad story."

31:54.456 --> 31:58.627
Julia has been tested
for everything under the Sun,

31:58.669 --> 32:00.921
several times.

32:00.963 --> 32:03.340
I guess they have
their own motives

32:03.382 --> 32:05.843
for being interested
in Julia's story.

32:05.884 --> 32:09.471
But I can't imagine
any medical professional

32:09.513 --> 32:13.350
who holds a high position
in the CDC calling a patient

32:13.392 --> 32:17.187
to deter them from treatment
of any disease.

32:17.229 --> 32:19.523
How does that make sense?

32:19.565 --> 32:22.568
[ambient nature sounds]

32:25.320 --> 32:29.741
- Investigate the CDC!
Investigate Lyme disease!

32:29.783 --> 32:35.539
Investigate the CDC!
Investigate Lyme disease!

32:37.040 --> 32:40.961
- Doctors need
to realize it's everywhere.

32:41.003 --> 32:43.881
I mean,
birds fly, animals roam,

32:43.922 --> 32:46.425
people travel
and pack their bags

32:46.466 --> 32:49.428
with clothing that they've
been out in the woods with.

32:49.469 --> 32:50.804
- Every doctor I've been to

32:50.846 --> 32:53.390
is saying, like,
"We don't treat Lyme," or...

32:53.432 --> 32:54.892
- Yeah.
- "It's all in your head…"

32:54.933 --> 32:56.310
- Yeah.
- Or they'll see the strands.

32:56.351 --> 32:58.437
"Oh, is not--
is not the CDC positive?"

32:58.478 --> 33:00.939
- You see, that's--that's--
- "So you're fine."

33:00.981 --> 33:04.735
- Investigate the CDC!
Investigate Lyme disease!

33:06.612 --> 33:10.073
- We understand that patients
who don't feel well

33:10.115 --> 33:12.326
are desperate
and seeking answers.

33:12.367 --> 33:15.287
But we're concerned
that some of them

33:15.329 --> 33:18.040
fall into a trap
of being treated for things

33:18.081 --> 33:21.168
that ultimately
are not helping them.

33:21.210 --> 33:23.837
[tense music]

33:23.879 --> 33:26.423
- There are very powerful
forces standing in the way

33:26.465 --> 33:29.635
of progressive attitudes
towards Lyme,

33:29.676 --> 33:33.597
most notably
Centers for Disease Control

33:33.639 --> 33:37.976
because they are the leader
not just for this country

33:38.018 --> 33:40.479
but for all of the countries
in the world.

33:40.521 --> 33:44.525
And their intransigence
has created just--

33:44.566 --> 33:46.485
just a world of problems.

33:46.527 --> 33:48.028
[music building]

33:48.070 --> 33:49.279
In the early '90s,

33:49.321 --> 33:53.200
I was actually invited out
to CDC Fort Collins.

33:53.242 --> 33:55.160
You know, I gave a talk there.

33:55.202 --> 33:57.913
And afterwards,
we all went out to ski.

33:59.081 --> 34:01.166
I've had very good relations
with many of the folks

34:01.208 --> 34:03.210
at CDC over many years.

34:03.252 --> 34:04.878
It's not the people.

34:04.920 --> 34:06.797
It's the policies.

34:06.839 --> 34:11.134
And the question is,
who sets CDC policies, and why?

34:11.176 --> 34:17.266
♪ ♪

34:19.518 --> 34:23.438
- One of my major stories
for the "Poughkeepsie Journal"

34:23.480 --> 34:27.650
was when I obtained
a sheaf of emails,

34:27.693 --> 34:30.737
2,500 pages, actually.

34:32.072 --> 34:36.827
These emails were between
the major players in Lyme disease

34:36.869 --> 34:41.956
as well as officials
in the CDC and NIH.

34:41.998 --> 34:48.045
The emails belied a sort of
"us against them" mentality.

34:48.088 --> 34:50.841
In one email,
this researcher from Yale

34:50.882 --> 34:53.677
by the name of Durland Fish
was commenting

34:53.719 --> 34:56.263
how Lyme disease groups
were organizing.

34:56.304 --> 34:58.932
They were holding protests.

34:58.974 --> 35:02.561
What he said was,
"This battle cannot be won

35:02.603 --> 35:04.354
"on a scientific front.

35:04.396 --> 35:08.108
"We need to mount
a sociopolitical offensive.

35:08.150 --> 35:10.736
"But we are outnumbered
and outgunned.

35:10.777 --> 35:14.323
We need reinforcements
from outside our field."

35:18.076 --> 35:21.413
There was another
very telling email.

35:21.455 --> 35:25.542
In 2007, Phil Baker was leaving

35:25.584 --> 35:28.212
the National Institutes of Health.

35:28.253 --> 35:32.341
He was the person
who decided on grants

35:32.382 --> 35:34.927
for Lyme disease research.

35:34.968 --> 35:38.180
And what he said was,
"I'll certainly miss

35:38.222 --> 35:40.974
"all of you people--
the scientists--

35:41.016 --> 35:44.311
but not the Lyme loonies."

35:47.189 --> 35:49.816
When I asked him
for a comment,

35:49.858 --> 35:54.488
he said, "That might be
too kind a description."

35:56.240 --> 36:00.953
And one more, from an official
at the National Institutes of Health:

36:00.994 --> 36:03.997
"What we have here is a war,

36:04.039 --> 36:08.627
"an insurgency against
evidence-based medicine.

36:08.669 --> 36:11.296
It's time to start
shooting back."

36:14.883 --> 36:17.886
[birds singing]

36:27.437 --> 36:29.356
- It's such a bad article,
the computer doesn't even

36:29.398 --> 36:31.108
want to open it up.

36:32.734 --> 36:34.111
[laughs]

36:34.152 --> 36:35.779
That happens sometimes.

36:37.614 --> 36:40.784
"Antiscience."
Huh.

36:41.785 --> 36:44.538
Who, like,
publishes this stuff?

36:44.580 --> 36:47.541
[inquisitive music]

36:47.583 --> 36:54.590
♪ ♪

36:57.426 --> 37:01.597
So one of the problems
with these antiscience articles--

37:01.638 --> 37:04.141
they sort of make
these broad claims.

37:04.183 --> 37:06.435
And then they make it,
like, people like me,

37:06.476 --> 37:10.522
who would question
the testing, the treatment,

37:10.564 --> 37:14.359
and try to lump me into people
who believe, you know,

37:14.401 --> 37:17.487
that the Moon doesn't exist
and the world is flat.

37:17.529 --> 37:19.406
And they're deflecting
the real issues.

37:22.409 --> 37:25.829
What kind of a disease is it
that you're ostracized

37:25.871 --> 37:28.790
by the very community
that should be helping you?

37:28.832 --> 37:30.876
I don't think you have
to have an MD to think

37:30.918 --> 37:32.753
there's something wrong here.

37:32.794 --> 37:35.339
What is it that these people
have in common?

37:35.380 --> 37:36.715
And you could either say
they all have in common

37:36.757 --> 37:38.133
that they're crazy,

37:38.175 --> 37:40.385
or you could say there's,
like, something out there

37:40.427 --> 37:41.803
that's causing this.

37:41.845 --> 37:45.098
[bell tolling]

37:45.140 --> 37:47.309
This may be some
of the first Lyme science

37:47.351 --> 37:48.644
being done on this campus.

37:48.685 --> 37:50.604
And in fact,
some of these projects

37:50.646 --> 37:53.023
are really the first
to be done in this country.

37:54.191 --> 37:56.360
These are ideas
that I've been working on

37:56.401 --> 37:57.861
and my colleagues
have been working on

37:57.903 --> 38:00.656
in the cancer field
for, you know, 20-plus years,

38:00.697 --> 38:04.535
and now we're finally gonna be
applying this to Lyme disease.

38:14.795 --> 38:17.756
What if I told you
that we could image

38:17.798 --> 38:19.424
Lyme disease in your body?

38:19.466 --> 38:21.635
[machine whirring]

38:21.677 --> 38:24.638
[inquisitive music]

38:24.680 --> 38:27.140
♪ ♪

38:27.182 --> 38:29.351
Can you imagine going
to a doctor and say,

38:29.393 --> 38:31.395
"Wow, you've got pain
in your left knee.

38:31.436 --> 38:33.188
"That's kind of interesting,
because this scan

38:33.230 --> 38:36.191
is lighting up for Borrelia
in your left knee."

38:37.651 --> 38:42.072
So we could actually show,
on a noninvasive scan,

38:42.114 --> 38:44.533
that you've got the bugs
in your body,

38:44.575 --> 38:47.202
and you've got 'em
where your symptoms are.

38:48.328 --> 38:50.539
We don't have
anything like this.

38:50.581 --> 38:52.332
It's all guesswork.

38:52.374 --> 38:54.168
I mean,
just like it is for cancer,

38:54.209 --> 38:57.087
this would be revolutionary

38:57.129 --> 38:59.590
in the way we diagnose

38:59.631 --> 39:01.717
and then the way we treat.

39:03.760 --> 39:07.514
Since my transplant,
I realized that this field

39:07.556 --> 39:10.517
is sorely lacking,
bad diagnostics.

39:10.559 --> 39:13.145
We need better therapies.
All of you know that.

39:13.187 --> 39:17.024
What I'm saying is that we can
and we will do better.

39:17.065 --> 39:18.817
I'm gonna make you
that promise right here.

39:22.070 --> 39:26.116
The timeline that I promised
to deliver is three years.

39:26.158 --> 39:27.618
I mean, that's,
like, unheard of.

39:27.659 --> 39:29.203
But that's the pressure
I'm putting

39:29.244 --> 39:31.496
on myself and everyone else.

39:31.538 --> 39:33.624
That's, like, a heavy burden,
when I know, like,

39:33.665 --> 39:36.376
what the desperation is,
when people are like,

39:36.418 --> 39:39.671
"Well, Neil, you're it.
You got to deliver for us."

39:39.713 --> 39:42.716
So, um,

39:42.758 --> 39:45.135
I'm gonna deliver for people.

39:56.813 --> 40:01.235
- After the pope, Julia was
taking a turn for the worse.

40:02.694 --> 40:04.404
I knew that I had
to find somebody

40:04.446 --> 40:07.324
that was willing to treat Julia
for Lyme disease.

40:08.909 --> 40:10.911
And I started to realize
that there's such a thing

40:10.953 --> 40:12.871
called Lyme-literate doctors.

40:15.207 --> 40:17.334
Everyone I would call
would have a waiting list

40:17.376 --> 40:19.211
of six to eight months.

40:20.671 --> 40:22.548
You know, all these doctors
are not covered

40:22.589 --> 40:24.132
by insurance companies.

40:26.885 --> 40:29.221
It all seemed
a little sketchy.

40:36.061 --> 40:37.354
- Over here.

40:39.398 --> 40:41.191
Take a nice, deep breath.

40:41.233 --> 40:42.985
Good.

40:43.026 --> 40:44.403
Let me see with your reflexes.

40:47.739 --> 40:49.867
Yeah, they're cold.

40:49.908 --> 40:51.785
Now, if you start
to feel really, really dizzy

40:51.827 --> 40:53.203
with this,
I will sit you down.

40:53.245 --> 40:56.248
I just want to see how fast
your heart rate starts to go up.

40:56.290 --> 40:57.583
- Okay, go ahead.
- All right.

40:59.042 --> 41:00.335
Okay.

41:00.377 --> 41:03.255
I'll try and do this for at least,
if you can, just for one minute,

41:03.297 --> 41:05.382
so I can get a sense
what the pulse rate's running.

41:05.424 --> 41:07.384
- [inaudible]
- Is it already difficult?

41:07.426 --> 41:08.594
- Yeah, yeah.
Down, down, down, down.

41:08.635 --> 41:10.345
- If you have to sit down,
it's okay.

41:10.387 --> 41:11.805
- [inaudible]
- Dad, Dad, Dad.

41:11.847 --> 41:13.182
Just down.
- [inaudible]

41:13.223 --> 41:14.224
- Okay, go ahead. Go ahead.
- Down. Down.

41:14.266 --> 41:15.684
- Go down.

41:18.353 --> 41:19.521
- Let me just
check the pulse now.

41:20.898 --> 41:22.524
[tense music]

41:22.566 --> 41:25.068
I've never seen anyone
have a heart rate of 250.

41:25.110 --> 41:27.779
- Mm-hmm.
- That's--that's off the wall.

41:29.239 --> 41:31.867
When I was looking for answers
for Lyme patients,

41:31.909 --> 41:33.785
I discovered
that there were multiple reasons

41:33.827 --> 41:35.037
why people stayed ill.

41:35.078 --> 41:36.914
It was like going
to a doctor's office

41:36.955 --> 41:40.000
with 16 nails in your foot,
saying you have foot pain.

41:40.042 --> 41:41.502
And the doctor
pulls out one nail

41:41.543 --> 41:42.920
and says,
"Come back in a month."

41:42.961 --> 41:44.630
You still have 15 nails
in your foot.

41:44.671 --> 41:45.881
You're gonna have pain.

41:45.923 --> 41:48.383
Some of it is that the Lyme
organism is persisting,

41:48.425 --> 41:50.761
but part of it
is also other infections.

41:50.802 --> 41:52.721
Right now, there are
at least 18 different

41:52.763 --> 41:54.848
tick-borne diseases
that can be transmitted

41:54.890 --> 41:56.642
by the bite of a tick.

42:00.521 --> 42:02.523
You know, the most common
coinfections that we see

42:02.564 --> 42:05.776
that make people ill is Lyme,
babesia, and bartonella. Right?

42:05.817 --> 42:07.528
And when you
put them all together,

42:07.569 --> 42:09.947
the people get
much, much sicker.

42:09.988 --> 42:12.157
- The first appointment
with Dr. Horowitz,

42:12.199 --> 42:14.952
when I realized that they
didn't accept insurance,

42:14.993 --> 42:16.286
you know, that was a red flag.

42:16.328 --> 42:20.040
I realize now
that it's not a red flag.

42:20.082 --> 42:22.417
That first visit,
I think it was anywhere

42:22.459 --> 42:24.628
between three and four hours.

42:24.670 --> 42:29.049
And so much was revealed to me
about Julia's situation.

42:30.759 --> 42:32.052
- I was in insurance companies.

42:32.094 --> 42:34.429
I accepted Medicare
for at least 25 years.

42:34.471 --> 42:35.889
There just got to be a point

42:35.931 --> 42:38.308
when the insurance companies
dropped me.

42:38.350 --> 42:40.018
There was just no way
to continue in that way,

42:40.060 --> 42:41.520
and I had to go
outside the system.

42:41.562 --> 42:44.064
[tense music]

42:44.106 --> 42:47.609
I lost about 2,000 patients
within a period of six months

42:47.651 --> 42:48.944
because I was
spending too much

42:48.986 --> 42:50.779
of the insurance
company's money

42:50.821 --> 42:53.323
for a disease
that didn't exist.

42:53.365 --> 42:56.118
It was like,
hear no evil, see no evil.

42:56.159 --> 42:58.579
They just didn't want
to know about it.

42:58.620 --> 43:05.586
♪ ♪

43:05.627 --> 43:10.174
- Lyme disease is the first
disease of epidemic proportion

43:10.215 --> 43:12.593
that came to light
hand in hand

43:12.634 --> 43:15.470
with the development
of managed care.

43:15.512 --> 43:18.223
- When HMO medicine
started taking effect

43:18.265 --> 43:20.350
in the 1980s and '90s,

43:20.392 --> 43:21.977
it was easy
to practice medicine

43:22.019 --> 43:24.062
for people
that had straight diseases

43:24.104 --> 43:26.481
like high blood pressure,
high cholesterol, diabetes.

43:26.523 --> 43:28.400
I could get them in and out
in 10 to 15 minutes.

43:28.442 --> 43:29.484
That was simple.

43:29.526 --> 43:32.821
The problem with Lyme disease is,
they have up to 38 different symptoms.

43:32.863 --> 43:36.325
You can't get that done
in 12 to 15 minutes.

43:36.366 --> 43:39.077
- So here's a disease that's
affecting a lot of people,

43:39.119 --> 43:42.789
can be costly, and there's
been a very active role

43:42.831 --> 43:47.753
of the insurers, their agents,
to define

43:47.794 --> 43:52.007
not Lyme disease away
but chronic Lyme disease away.

43:52.049 --> 43:54.676
[static buzzes]

43:54.718 --> 43:57.846
I want to introduce everybody.
This is Vicki Logan.

43:57.888 --> 44:01.517
And it is June 22, 2001.

44:01.558 --> 44:06.230
You are a former
pediatric ICU nurse, correct?

44:06.271 --> 44:08.565
So you were
a highly skilled professional.

44:10.025 --> 44:11.485
- And highly educated.

44:11.527 --> 44:13.695
[tense music]

44:13.737 --> 44:16.240
Vicki Logan was a fairly early
patient that I saw,

44:16.281 --> 44:18.534
around '88 or '89.

44:18.575 --> 44:22.412
She presented a mystery
that hadn't been solved.

44:22.454 --> 44:25.040
When she came to me, I studied her
very carefully for a year,

44:25.082 --> 44:26.625
did all kinds of testing,

44:26.667 --> 44:28.168
everything that I knew
how to do,

44:28.210 --> 44:29.461
not just for Lyme disease
but for other,

44:29.503 --> 44:32.297
you know, conditions.

44:32.339 --> 44:35.551
I knew that she had grown up
in Westchester County,

44:35.592 --> 44:38.178
and I knew that it was
a very tick-infested area.

44:38.220 --> 44:40.222
Realizing that she was sick
and getting worse,

44:40.264 --> 44:42.766
I felt that it was appropriate
to treat her

44:42.808 --> 44:44.893
for the possibility
that she might have Lyme.

44:44.935 --> 44:46.436
♪ ♪

44:46.478 --> 44:50.190
About a year later,
she begged me for a spinal tap.

44:50.232 --> 44:52.234
I put a couple
of ccs of spinal fluid

44:52.276 --> 44:56.280
in a special culture
and shipped it off to the CDC.

44:57.698 --> 45:00.492
Several weeks later, I got
an excited telephone call

45:00.534 --> 45:03.328
from David Dennis
from CDC Fort Collins

45:03.370 --> 45:05.706
to let me know that spirochetes

45:05.747 --> 45:07.916
were growing
out of her spinal fluid.

45:09.376 --> 45:11.128
He was quite excited about it

45:11.170 --> 45:13.380
and actually
rather incredulous,

45:13.422 --> 45:16.216
because he knew that she had
already been treated

45:16.258 --> 45:18.468
with a regimen
that was supposed

45:18.510 --> 45:20.554
to eradicate Lyme disease.

45:22.139 --> 45:24.474
And at that point,
then I really knew what she had.

45:24.516 --> 45:28.979
And I treated you
for 109 continuous days,

45:29.021 --> 45:31.607
and you progressively
improved.

45:32.399 --> 45:34.193
But at a certain point,

45:34.234 --> 45:37.446
policies changed
at Empire Blue Cross Blue Shield

45:37.487 --> 45:40.616
that made it almost impossible
for people like Vicki

45:40.657 --> 45:42.910
to receive the treatment
that she needed.

45:44.077 --> 45:45.704
There would be
no reimbursement for--

45:45.746 --> 45:47.372
for that kind of care.

45:50.083 --> 45:51.627
In the late 1990s,

45:51.668 --> 45:56.256
Vicki and about a dozen
other patients filed a lawsuit

45:56.298 --> 45:58.759
against Empire Blue Cross Blue Shield.

45:58.800 --> 46:01.887
The litigating attorney was
a gentleman named Ira Maurer.

46:01.929 --> 46:04.223
And he brought suit
against Empire

46:04.264 --> 46:06.642
on behalf of these patients.

46:06.683 --> 46:09.228
- When you've got
lots of disagreement

46:09.269 --> 46:11.730
as to what
is appropriate diagnosis

46:11.772 --> 46:13.357
and treatment
of Lyme disease,

46:13.398 --> 46:15.776
it makes it very hard
for a Lyme disease patient

46:15.817 --> 46:19.821
and a lawyer like myself
to go in there and challenge

46:19.863 --> 46:22.574
when an insurance company
refuses to pay

46:22.616 --> 46:26.036
for very expensive intravenous
antibiotic treatment.

46:27.788 --> 46:30.040
- One of the most revealing

46:30.082 --> 46:33.335
documents in the Lyme annals

46:33.377 --> 46:36.797
emerged from the case
of Vicki Logan.

46:36.839 --> 46:40.175
One of the witnesses
that came on to give testimony

46:40.217 --> 46:41.593
was Richard Sanchez,

46:41.635 --> 46:44.179
who worked
for the insurance company.

46:44.221 --> 46:47.975
He really detailed,
in a disturbing way,

46:48.016 --> 46:51.019
the way in which
insurance companies

46:51.061 --> 46:55.440
red-flagged Lyme disease
and put up roadblocks.

46:57.192 --> 46:59.152
- They raised the bar,
made it harder for people

46:59.194 --> 47:02.573
to qualify for the expensive
IV treatment,

47:02.614 --> 47:04.491
knowing that there were
some people

47:04.533 --> 47:08.829
who still would benefit from it
and wouldn't qualify.

47:08.871 --> 47:13.250
And he considered those people
to be the "low-hanging fruit,"

47:13.292 --> 47:16.920
the easy money to make
for the insurance company.

47:16.962 --> 47:20.924
- In the meantime,
some of the same people who created

47:20.966 --> 47:24.094
the Infectious Diseases Society of America
guidelines

47:24.136 --> 47:26.597
were consulting
with the insurers

47:26.638 --> 47:30.058
on their internal Lyme disease
guidelines policy.

47:31.894 --> 47:34.313
- So they created the guidelines
on the one hand,

47:34.354 --> 47:36.398
and then on the other hand,
they're getting, you know,

47:36.440 --> 47:41.069
$600 an hour in the 1990s
to deny these cases.

47:42.070 --> 47:47.576
Leonard Sigal said his fee
in 1996 was $560 an hour,

47:47.618 --> 47:49.870
and he even quipped
that it was quite helpful

47:49.912 --> 47:52.831
in meeting college tuition for his kids.

47:52.873 --> 47:56.460
- There's good proof that one
can do significant damage

47:56.502 --> 48:00.214
to patients by putting them
on long-term intravenous antibiotics.

48:00.255 --> 48:02.508
- If one side
in this controversy

48:02.549 --> 48:05.719
writes the protocol
and says no one may be treated

48:05.761 --> 48:08.680
beyond 28 days
with intravenous antibiotics,

48:08.722 --> 48:11.475
that's going to be disastrous
for patients with Lyme disease.

48:13.852 --> 48:18.273
- There was a move
by some of the insiders

48:18.315 --> 48:22.069
of the Infectious Diseases Society
to issue guidelines.

48:23.111 --> 48:25.531
I was part
of the original guidelines.

48:25.572 --> 48:27.699
I tried to advise
that we weren't ready

48:27.741 --> 48:29.451
to issue guidelines
about long-term disease.

48:29.493 --> 48:31.161
We didn't have the information.

48:31.203 --> 48:34.957
You have to be really careful
about issuing guidelines,

48:34.998 --> 48:36.375
'cause they get abused.

48:37.835 --> 48:39.711
The overseers said,
"We need to put out

48:39.753 --> 48:41.171
these Lyme disease guidelines."

48:41.213 --> 48:43.131
And there was some urgency
to do something.

48:43.173 --> 48:44.925
I mean, there's
Lyme disease out there.

48:46.260 --> 48:47.719
I said,
"Well, we're not ready,

48:47.761 --> 48:50.389
but I could
provide the language."

48:50.430 --> 48:54.101
"There are patients
who have ongoing symptoms

48:54.142 --> 48:57.437
"for which
the causation is unknown,

48:57.479 --> 49:00.858
"and it's to be left to the judgment
of the physician

49:00.899 --> 49:02.651
as to how to manage this."

49:03.944 --> 49:06.071
But that went too far
for them.

49:06.113 --> 49:10.784
And they removed my draft
and put in their own draft.

49:10.826 --> 49:13.203
It's like chronic Lyme disease
doesn't exist.

49:14.538 --> 49:16.373
That was Dr. Wormser.

49:16.415 --> 49:19.626
He issued a final declaration
as far as,

49:19.668 --> 49:21.503
"You can sign it,
but we're not gonna

49:21.545 --> 49:23.922
have a minority report,"
if you will.

49:23.964 --> 49:25.716
And so you're stuck.

49:25.757 --> 49:27.593
How are you gonna
undo something?

49:27.634 --> 49:29.052
Who's gonna back off?

49:31.513 --> 49:33.098
- Unfortunately,
I've seen people

49:33.140 --> 49:34.766
whose lives were destroyed

49:34.808 --> 49:37.436
because they went years
and years and years

49:37.477 --> 49:41.940
with no treatment
or inadequate treatment.

49:41.982 --> 49:43.942
And it ate away
at their bodies

49:43.984 --> 49:45.527
and their brains,

49:45.569 --> 49:49.156
at their organs,
until they succumbed.

49:49.198 --> 49:52.743
So it's a very complex situation,

49:52.784 --> 49:55.037
and the insurance companies
have made use

49:55.078 --> 49:58.582
of that complexity
to their economic advantage.

49:59.333 --> 50:02.628
- In my opinion, no way
was her care experimental.

50:02.669 --> 50:05.339
Her care was absolutely
medically necessary.

50:05.380 --> 50:07.633
And the necessity of it
was demonstrated--

50:07.674 --> 50:09.343
whenever she stopped
being treated,

50:09.384 --> 50:12.095
she would deteriorate
in objectively measurable ways,

50:12.137 --> 50:14.139
and when she got treated,
she would improve

50:14.181 --> 50:17.267
in objectively measurable ways.

50:17.309 --> 50:19.353
Vicki went for a number of years

50:19.394 --> 50:21.063
without the treatment
that she needed,

50:21.104 --> 50:24.983
and during that time,
her condition deteriorated.

50:25.025 --> 50:27.069
One of her last stays
at Northern Westchester,

50:27.110 --> 50:29.613
I undertook a long interview
with her.

50:29.655 --> 50:32.616
Vicki, you want to take
a couple of minutes

50:32.658 --> 50:35.202
to say anything
from your own heart?

51:08.443 --> 51:11.989
- She experienced a series
of grand mal seizures.

51:12.030 --> 51:14.199
Her friend Rosalyn
said that Vicki, you know,

51:14.241 --> 51:16.118
mouthed to her, "I love you."

51:16.159 --> 51:19.621
And within a few days,
you know,

51:19.663 --> 51:21.123
she was dead.

51:23.584 --> 51:26.545
Vicki's case
was reported in the--

51:26.587 --> 51:28.547
in the "New York Times'"
Science Times,

51:28.589 --> 51:30.924
I think in August of 1993.

51:30.966 --> 51:34.052
I fully expected that,
you know,

51:34.094 --> 51:35.554
that would be a turning point.

51:35.596 --> 51:38.891
And it's just incredible to me
that here we are,

51:38.932 --> 51:40.726
you know,
pushing 30 years later,

51:40.767 --> 51:43.478
and there's still
so much controversy

51:43.520 --> 51:46.815
and so much difficulty
for the patients.

51:48.066 --> 51:50.944
Let me tell you,
the deck was stacked against,

51:50.986 --> 51:53.447
you know, Vicki
and patients like her.

51:55.616 --> 51:57.326
[video static crescendos]

52:02.956 --> 52:04.791
- I need you say,
"When I stand up,

52:04.833 --> 52:06.627
"although maybe I'm weak
and I can't walk,

52:06.668 --> 52:08.212
but I'm not gonna pass out."

52:08.253 --> 52:09.379
And that's
when I'm gonna know.

52:09.421 --> 52:10.923
And that's the thing you have
to understand is,

52:10.964 --> 52:12.508
till the blood pressure
is controlled,

52:12.549 --> 52:14.343
I can't do the physical therapy
for the legs.

52:14.384 --> 52:15.344
- Right, right.
- Right?

52:15.385 --> 52:17.304
And that's gonna be essential
to getting this whole thing done.

52:17.346 --> 52:18.764
- Absolutely.
- So that's why I'm trying

52:18.805 --> 52:21.350
to go as fast as I can
but in a safe manner.

52:21.391 --> 52:22.809
- Right, right, right, right.

52:28.398 --> 52:31.193
- Julia, if you could put your arm out
a little bit for me...

52:36.156 --> 52:37.991
- Okay.
[whimpers]

52:38.033 --> 52:39.826
Dad, I don't wanna.
- I know.

52:39.868 --> 52:41.161
Let him do the blood pressure.

52:41.203 --> 52:42.746
- [whines]

52:42.788 --> 52:45.582
- Okay, you can
put her back now.

52:45.624 --> 52:46.792
- Wait, stay here.

52:46.834 --> 52:48.293
- I'm staying. I'm staying.

52:49.837 --> 52:51.505
- Let me just check her pulse.

53:09.857 --> 53:12.568
- She's at 140 beats
per minute.

53:12.609 --> 53:14.486
- [groans]

53:14.528 --> 53:16.530
[tense music]

53:16.572 --> 53:17.823
- When you feel
like you're dying

53:17.865 --> 53:20.367
and there's
nothing else to try,

53:20.409 --> 53:22.369
you reach
for anything you can.

53:22.411 --> 53:23.704
You have to take that risk.

53:24.663 --> 53:26.498
- Even if God came down
and told me,

53:26.540 --> 53:28.834
"You're doing the right thing,"
I'd be scared.

53:28.876 --> 53:32.296
I'm scared till this day,
giving her any medication.

53:34.840 --> 53:36.633
The hospitals wanted us

53:36.675 --> 53:39.678
to go into an in-patient
rehabilitation center

53:39.720 --> 53:43.765
to get physical therapy
and psychiatry.

53:43.807 --> 53:46.810
This is the only option
the hospitals gave me.

53:46.852 --> 53:49.229
They gave me nothing else.

53:49.271 --> 53:50.272
- You just say when, Julia.

53:52.024 --> 53:54.151
I'm starting now.

53:54.193 --> 53:56.403
- [whimpering]
Ow, ow, ow.

53:56.445 --> 53:58.155
- Nine seconds. Ten seconds.

53:58.197 --> 53:59.406
- Down, down.
Down.

53:59.448 --> 54:00.532
- Down? Down? You sure?

54:00.574 --> 54:01.700
- Down. Please go down.

54:01.742 --> 54:02.868
Go down, James.
- Try to get to 30.

54:02.910 --> 54:04.119
Try to get to 30.
- James, go down now.

54:04.161 --> 54:05.537
Please, James.

54:07.873 --> 54:09.499
- I know that Julia's had
plenty of breaks

54:09.541 --> 54:12.836
off of antibiotics
for several months at a time,

54:12.878 --> 54:16.298
and she's gotten sicker
off of medication.

54:16.340 --> 54:18.008
So what do you do?

54:18.884 --> 54:21.637
I can't just let her get worse.

54:21.678 --> 54:23.597
You know,
we have to try to fight

54:23.639 --> 54:26.725
until we feel like
we've exhausted everything.

54:26.767 --> 54:28.477
- Night sweats, hot and cold.

54:28.519 --> 54:30.270
Severe fatigue.
Shortness of breath.

54:30.312 --> 54:31.939
Sore throats
and swollen glands.

54:31.980 --> 54:34.399
Joint pain in the knuckles,
shoulders.

54:34.441 --> 54:36.276
Severe headaches.
Burning, tingling,

54:36.318 --> 54:38.153
and buzzing sensations
of the lower extremities

54:38.195 --> 54:39.446
with loss of sensation.

54:39.488 --> 54:41.782
Blurry vision.
Severe cognitive problems.

54:41.823 --> 54:44.034
This is five months
into this treatment.

54:44.076 --> 54:45.285
- Absolutely.
- The majority

54:45.327 --> 54:46.954
of all these symptoms
are better.

54:46.995 --> 54:49.581
- Don't open your eyes, Stephen,
until I tell you to open them.

54:49.623 --> 54:52.376
Don't touch your eyes!
Don't--

54:52.417 --> 54:54.837
all: ♪ Happy birthday… ♪

54:54.878 --> 54:56.964
- I was forced
to write this appeal

54:57.005 --> 54:59.800
because our insurance company
was calling Julia's condition

54:59.842 --> 55:02.094
"not medically necessary."

55:02.135 --> 55:05.472
I've paid high premiums
to my insurance company for years.

55:05.514 --> 55:09.226
The fact that we were abandoned
by the insurance company

55:09.268 --> 55:10.811
is unacceptable.

55:12.729 --> 55:14.439
We still have people
showing us love

55:14.481 --> 55:16.984
and showing us support.

55:17.025 --> 55:20.612
Unfortunately, though,
the funds aren't there anymore.

55:20.654 --> 55:22.281
Nobody really understands,
when you're dealing

55:22.322 --> 55:25.033
with chronic disease,
you know,

55:25.075 --> 55:27.160
treatment can go on
for a very long time.

55:27.202 --> 55:29.663
[indistinct chatter]

55:31.290 --> 55:34.209
