56:05.866 --> 56:08.827
[building tense music]

56:08.869 --> 56:15.876
♪ ♪

56:22.299 --> 56:24.134
[people screaming distantly]

56:24.176 --> 56:27.137
[fireworks popping and whistling]

56:28.472 --> 56:32.434
- When I'm with my friends,
even though I love my friends,

56:32.476 --> 56:34.811
it's amazing to see
what their priorities are

56:34.853 --> 56:37.523
and what mine are

56:37.564 --> 56:38.982
and what they think about

56:39.024 --> 56:42.110
when they're alone
in their bed at night

56:42.152 --> 56:43.779
and what I think about.

56:43.820 --> 56:45.989
[fireworks whistling]

56:49.284 --> 56:52.579
Looking at a girl
or boy my age,

56:52.621 --> 56:55.332
they kind of know
what their future's like.

56:55.374 --> 56:59.169
That they're gonna
go to college, get a job.

56:59.211 --> 57:02.548
But when I think about mine,
I just--

57:02.589 --> 57:04.842
I know what I want to do,
and I know what my goals are.

57:04.883 --> 57:08.720
And I just don't know
what I'm gonna be capable of.

57:08.762 --> 57:12.516
And I think that's the scary part
of this disease,

57:12.558 --> 57:14.643
that you don't know what
the next day is gonna be like.

57:22.901 --> 57:25.863
[tense music]

57:25.904 --> 57:29.741
♪ ♪

57:29.783 --> 57:33.161
- During the 1990s, there was
all this fighting going on,

57:33.203 --> 57:34.413
and I often wondered,

57:34.454 --> 57:37.332
what is going
to change people's minds?

57:39.042 --> 57:41.795
They didn't believe
that persistent infection

57:41.837 --> 57:45.048
after antibiotic treatment
was possible.

57:45.090 --> 57:48.218
Unless you can prove
the spirochete persists,

57:48.260 --> 57:52.639
repeated antibiotic therapy
makes absolutely no sense.

57:52.681 --> 57:55.642
And I agree with them,
that that is a fundamental thing

57:55.684 --> 57:57.769
that you want
to be able to show.

57:58.896 --> 58:03.275
What totally changed the world
of Lyme disease research

58:03.317 --> 58:08.113
was in 2008, when one
of the world's best researchers

58:08.155 --> 58:11.408
on Lyme disease
published a paper showing that,

58:11.450 --> 58:16.496
despite antibiotic treatment,
the spirochete can persist.

58:16.538 --> 58:19.124
And then Monica Embers
at Tulane published her paper

58:19.166 --> 58:22.628
showing persistent infection
in the monkey model.

58:22.669 --> 58:25.172
So if that happens in the mouse model
and the monkey model,

58:25.214 --> 58:27.424
why wouldn't it happen
in the human?

58:29.218 --> 58:32.888
- I lead the vector-borne
diseases corps here

58:32.930 --> 58:35.474
at the Tulane Primate Center.

58:35.516 --> 58:38.435
I can infect
ten different monkeys

58:38.477 --> 58:40.896
with the same strain
of Borrelli burgdorferi

58:40.938 --> 58:42.814
and see
very different outcomes

58:42.856 --> 58:44.608
after antibiotic treatment.

58:45.943 --> 58:48.695
What we found--some were
infected in the heart.

58:48.737 --> 58:50.822
Some were infected
in the joints.

58:50.864 --> 58:52.866
And probably the most
surprising aspect of it

58:52.908 --> 58:56.286
was that we found
multiple spirochetes in the brains

58:56.328 --> 58:59.831
of two of our
doxycycline-treated monkeys.

58:59.873 --> 59:02.042
We know that they persisted.

59:03.377 --> 59:06.755
- We're dealing
with a very unique situation here.

59:06.797 --> 59:08.382
The current Lyme antibiotic

59:08.423 --> 59:12.803
does not completely eradicate
Borrelli bacteria.

59:12.845 --> 59:16.056
We found
this dandelion phenomenon.

59:16.098 --> 59:19.184
The mower is equivalent
to the antibiotics

59:19.226 --> 59:21.186
that chopped off the top part.

59:21.228 --> 59:24.106
But because the root,
the persister, is still there,

59:24.147 --> 59:25.774
they can grow back.

59:25.816 --> 59:28.485
You need drugs
targeting both parts

59:28.527 --> 59:31.363
in order
to more effectively cure

59:31.405 --> 59:33.907
these persistent form
of the disease.

59:35.534 --> 59:38.912
- I think the future
is good science

59:38.954 --> 59:42.666
engaging top-notch researchers
and getting them excited

59:42.708 --> 59:45.544
about the opportunities
in this field.

59:45.586 --> 59:49.214
I've always stressed
that I think this field

59:49.256 --> 59:51.842
could use people from the outside
taking a fresh look.

59:52.718 --> 59:55.053
Just to be sitting
in one place together,

59:55.095 --> 59:59.057
talking about the issues,
I've got very high hopes,

59:59.099 --> 01:00:01.894
as do, I think,
everyone on the team,

01:00:01.935 --> 01:00:04.521
that we're heading
in a very good direction.

01:00:05.647 --> 01:00:07.941
- When I was at Tulane,
sitting in a room with, like,

01:00:07.983 --> 01:00:09.985
15 people from all these
major universities,

01:00:10.027 --> 01:00:12.654
all top researchers
in their field,

01:00:12.696 --> 01:00:14.615
and for the first time ever,

01:00:14.656 --> 01:00:16.325
they were all in there in the same room,

01:00:16.366 --> 01:00:18.577
saying, "Okay, chronic Lyme,

01:00:18.619 --> 01:00:19.828
"we may not have a cure.

01:00:19.870 --> 01:00:21.872
"Chronic Bartonella,
we may not have a cure.

01:00:21.914 --> 01:00:23.081
Let's work on this problem."

01:00:23.123 --> 01:00:24.917
It's super hopeful.

01:00:24.958 --> 01:00:26.293
But you still have these doctors

01:00:26.335 --> 01:00:28.003
who are digging their heels
in the sand.

01:00:28.045 --> 01:00:30.380
They're recognizing that there's--
a tide is turning,

01:00:30.422 --> 01:00:32.257
and they're becoming
more vocal.

01:00:33.175 --> 01:00:35.427
If you have three major
universities that come out--

01:00:35.469 --> 01:00:37.471
Johns Hopkins, Tulane,
and Northeastern--

01:00:37.513 --> 01:00:40.390
saying, "We can't kill Lyme
effectively in a test tube,"

01:00:40.432 --> 01:00:41.642
then you have a major problem.

01:00:41.683 --> 01:00:42.643
You have a major problem,

01:00:42.684 --> 01:00:44.603
because your position becomes
increasingly untenable.

01:00:44.645 --> 01:00:46.188
We have all this animal data
showing

01:00:46.230 --> 01:00:47.689
that we're not curing
the monkeys,

01:00:47.731 --> 01:00:49.566
we're not curing the dogs,
we're not curing the mice,

01:00:49.608 --> 01:00:51.109
and we're not
curing the horses

01:00:51.151 --> 01:00:52.861
with the same
antibiotic regimens

01:00:52.903 --> 01:00:55.489
you're supposed to,
you know, cure people.

01:00:55.531 --> 01:00:57.741
Of course it's gonna change.
Look, the truth is the truth,

01:00:57.783 --> 01:00:59.660
and eventually,
it comes to the surface.

01:00:59.701 --> 01:01:01.745
But it's bubbling up
very slowly,

01:01:01.787 --> 01:01:04.790
like--like, glacially slowly,

01:01:04.831 --> 01:01:07.793
too slow for people
who are desperately ill.

01:01:07.835 --> 01:01:10.504
♪ ♪

01:01:10.546 --> 01:01:14.341
- For years, the federal government
has spent very little

01:01:14.383 --> 01:01:17.803
to look into the problems
of Lyme disease.

01:01:17.845 --> 01:01:21.098
Compare that
to private foundations,

01:01:21.139 --> 01:01:24.726
which have spent something
on the order of $100 million

01:01:24.768 --> 01:01:28.063
in recent years
on research that today

01:01:28.105 --> 01:01:30.858
is answering
some of the key questions

01:01:30.899 --> 01:01:34.653
that weren't even being asked
by the federal government,

01:01:34.695 --> 01:01:38.282
by the traditional
mainstream researchers.

01:01:39.116 --> 01:01:42.160
They have written over and over

01:01:42.202 --> 01:01:44.997
that Lyme disease
is not chronic.

01:01:45.038 --> 01:01:48.458
They have published
in major American journals.

01:01:48.500 --> 01:01:52.671
And the journals
are as invested in that view

01:01:52.713 --> 01:01:57.759
as are these researchers,
as is the CDC and the NIH.

01:01:59.052 --> 01:02:01.763
So to walk away from that now

01:02:01.805 --> 01:02:05.475
would be very difficult
for them to do.

01:02:15.611 --> 01:02:17.070
- We've come a long way

01:02:17.112 --> 01:02:19.489
from when this seemed
like a pipe dream,

01:02:19.531 --> 01:02:21.533
like, "Yeah, wow,
wouldn't this be great

01:02:21.575 --> 01:02:23.452
if we could actually
image Borrelia?"

01:02:23.493 --> 01:02:25.412
And here we are,
you know, two years later,

01:02:25.454 --> 01:02:28.290
waiting to see
this all-important experiment.

01:02:28.332 --> 01:02:31.043
You know, a year from now,
we'll be looking at a scan

01:02:31.084 --> 01:02:34.087
of the first patient
getting this...

01:02:34.129 --> 01:02:35.339
hopefully.

01:02:35.380 --> 01:02:39.718
The current tests, you know,
only continue to fuel the debate

01:02:39.760 --> 01:02:42.054
of whether chronic symptoms
are related

01:02:42.095 --> 01:02:46.850
to the persistence
of living bacteria

01:02:46.892 --> 01:02:51.813
or whether they're related to,
you know, some other cause.

01:02:51.855 --> 01:02:55.359
If you could image this in the body,
I think that removes all doubt.

01:02:55.400 --> 01:02:57.569
I'm not sure there's
a controversy anymore.

01:02:57.611 --> 01:03:00.030
That, to me,
is pretty definitive evidence

01:03:00.072 --> 01:03:01.949
that you've got the bacteria

01:03:01.990 --> 01:03:05.077
and you need to be treated
for an active infection.

01:03:05.118 --> 01:03:07.204
I should have told these bacteria,
"Don't piss me off."

01:03:27.391 --> 01:03:29.434
- Oh. Whoa.
- Oh, wow.

01:03:29.476 --> 01:03:31.228
both: Whoa.
- Whoa.

01:03:31.270 --> 01:03:32.855
Look at that.
- Okay. [laughs]

01:03:32.896 --> 01:03:34.231
- Starry sky.

01:03:34.273 --> 01:03:36.358
Look at that.
- Oh, my gosh.

01:03:36.400 --> 01:03:39.736
- That is, like,
spirochete city.

01:03:39.778 --> 01:03:41.405
- You can see aggregates.
- Oh, my God.

01:03:41.446 --> 01:03:43.282
- You can see a little bit
of smearing

01:03:43.323 --> 01:03:45.200
and then a bunch of what looks
to be individuals.

01:03:45.242 --> 01:03:47.244
- That's, like, unbelievable.
Look at that.

01:03:48.161 --> 01:03:49.413
This is in the heart.

01:03:49.454 --> 01:03:50.831
- Yup.

01:03:53.208 --> 01:03:55.460
- What if you could
attach a toxin

01:03:55.502 --> 01:03:57.504
that just wipes
those cells out?

01:03:57.546 --> 01:03:59.381
I mean,
that's the magic bullet.

01:03:59.423 --> 01:04:00.716
- Yup.
- Right?

01:04:00.757 --> 01:04:04.303
Kill the target.
Avoid the normal tissue.

01:04:04.344 --> 01:04:07.097
This is it.

01:04:07.139 --> 01:04:08.974
This is, like,
proof of concept.

01:04:09.016 --> 01:04:11.143
We can actually do this.

01:04:11.185 --> 01:04:14.146
[soft dramatic music]

01:04:14.188 --> 01:04:15.939
♪ ♪

01:04:15.981 --> 01:04:17.441
Appropriate diagnosis
and treatment.

01:04:17.482 --> 01:04:19.067
It's gonna save lives.

01:04:20.944 --> 01:04:23.363
And you know what,
and vindication for everyone

01:04:23.405 --> 01:04:27.868
who has been denied care
and told that they're crazy.

01:04:27.910 --> 01:04:29.369
This is, like, for you.

01:04:30.913 --> 01:04:32.789
Told, "It's all in your head."

01:04:32.831 --> 01:04:34.166
But you know what,
it is all in your head.

01:04:34.208 --> 01:04:35.751
It's right there.

01:04:37.669 --> 01:04:39.254
It's in your head.
It's in your heart.

01:04:39.296 --> 01:04:42.341
It's in your ear.
It's in your joints.

01:04:54.853 --> 01:04:58.649
Good science
will trump bad behavior.

01:05:00.067 --> 01:05:02.903
And when that change happens,
hopefully it won't just be

01:05:02.945 --> 01:05:05.656
at the level
of clinical practice,

01:05:05.697 --> 01:05:09.868
but it'll be public policy,
it'll be insurance coverage,

01:05:09.910 --> 01:05:12.913
and all the other injustices
that have really been

01:05:12.955 --> 01:05:16.875
perpetuated will sort of fall
by the wayside.

01:05:16.917 --> 01:05:20.212
I'm very hopeful of the work
that we're doing.

01:05:20.254 --> 01:05:24.007
Every day that I come in,
I push our team.

01:05:24.049 --> 01:05:28.053
I implore them.
They all know your stories.

01:05:28.095 --> 01:05:30.764
- Please join me
in welcoming Neil Spector.

01:05:30.806 --> 01:05:32.182
Neil?

01:05:32.224 --> 01:05:34.601
[applause]

01:05:34.643 --> 01:05:38.856
- I want to tell you,
I think, a hopeful story.

01:05:38.897 --> 01:05:40.858
We want to develop
a "theranostic"--

01:05:40.899 --> 01:05:43.610
a therapeutic diagnostic
in one molecule.

01:05:43.652 --> 01:05:44.611
- Here you are.
You're a physician.

01:05:44.653 --> 01:05:47.990
You're connected.
- We need more research in this area.

01:05:48.031 --> 01:05:50.701
That's one of my missions
is to raise awareness

01:05:50.742 --> 01:05:53.161
that this is not a disease
that's easily diagnosed

01:05:53.203 --> 01:05:55.622
and easily cured,
as many believe.

01:05:55.664 --> 01:05:57.583
- Here is Dr. Neil Spector.

01:05:57.624 --> 01:05:58.792
[applause]

01:05:58.834 --> 01:06:01.461
- Thank you.
It's a great pleasure to be here.

01:06:01.503 --> 01:06:05.048
This is my ten-year anniversary
of my transplant

01:06:05.090 --> 01:06:08.093
from a misdiagnosis
of Lyme disease.

01:06:10.679 --> 01:06:13.265
I know what it's like,
in a very tangible, real way,

01:06:13.307 --> 01:06:15.642
to face your mortality.

01:06:15.684 --> 01:06:18.937
So, you know,
I'm not somebody who doesn't

01:06:18.979 --> 01:06:21.982
speak the language
of those suffering.

01:06:22.024 --> 01:06:24.026
[cheers and applause]

01:06:24.067 --> 01:06:26.278
It's hard, though.
You know, it's hard.

01:06:26.320 --> 01:06:29.031
I mean, I get fatigued.
I get tired.

01:06:29.072 --> 01:06:32.826
I need, frankly, to figure out
a better balance in my life,

01:06:32.868 --> 01:06:35.162
because there are times
when I feel

01:06:35.204 --> 01:06:37.289
like I'm heading
in a very bad direction

01:06:37.331 --> 01:06:41.960
and losing sort of perspective
on my own life.

01:06:46.507 --> 01:06:49.218
I may actually go home
and kind of relax

01:06:49.259 --> 01:06:52.095
for a little while
before the next trip.

01:06:52.137 --> 01:06:54.556
Hang out with my dog
and my family.

01:06:56.475 --> 01:06:58.685
That'll be good.

01:07:02.814 --> 01:07:05.817
[ambient sounds]

01:07:15.744 --> 01:07:20.958
- It's been very complicated,
as far as treatment goes.

01:07:20.999 --> 01:07:24.044
There's just not enough here
for Julia.

01:07:25.337 --> 01:07:28.048
Even though we've seen
tremendous improvements

01:07:28.090 --> 01:07:30.884
with Dr. Horowitz,

01:07:30.926 --> 01:07:34.346
it's been, like, almost impossible
to try to overcome certain things

01:07:34.388 --> 01:07:38.350
that I feel are really serious
in Julia's health.

01:07:38.392 --> 01:07:40.602
So I've been doing
a lot of research

01:07:40.644 --> 01:07:42.688
and looking at a lot
of different treatment options

01:07:42.729 --> 01:07:45.566
in other countries.

01:07:45.607 --> 01:07:47.359
The most promising thing
I found

01:07:47.401 --> 01:07:49.820
was embryonic stem cells
in India.

01:07:51.280 --> 01:07:53.031
Julia's been sick
for three years.

01:07:53.073 --> 01:07:55.367
I think we've tried
everything.

01:07:55.409 --> 01:07:56.952
There's one or two things
we haven't tried,

01:07:56.994 --> 01:07:58.495
and this is one of them.

01:07:59.788 --> 01:08:02.749
[tense music]

01:08:02.791 --> 01:08:09.631
♪ ♪

01:08:09.673 --> 01:08:12.259
Her diagnosis
for Lyme was missed.

01:08:13.385 --> 01:08:15.387
You know, doesn't seem

01:08:15.429 --> 01:08:17.723
like it's gonna be
an easy thing to fix.

01:08:37.451 --> 01:08:39.077
- May I start?

01:08:39.119 --> 01:08:41.121
Julia is a known case
of Lyme disease.

01:08:41.163 --> 01:08:42.581
Is that correct?
- That is correct.

01:08:42.622 --> 01:08:44.291
- And, Julia, how old are you?

01:08:44.333 --> 01:08:45.834
- 15.
- Are you aware

01:08:45.876 --> 01:08:47.878
that the [indistinct]
stem cell treatment

01:08:47.920 --> 01:08:49.421
is an experimental treatment

01:08:49.462 --> 01:08:51.715
and there are no guarantees
of any medical benefits

01:08:51.756 --> 01:08:53.050
it will bear?

01:08:53.091 --> 01:08:55.426
- Yes.
- And are you willing to undergo it?

01:08:55.469 --> 01:08:57.930
- Yes.
- Thank you.

01:08:57.970 --> 01:09:01.558
- You know, reading the consent,
I almost feel guilty.

01:09:01.600 --> 01:09:04.102
You know, you always feel like
you're making the wrong decisions.

01:09:04.144 --> 01:09:05.437
You don't know.

01:09:05.478 --> 01:09:08.523
You know, as sufferers,
we're vulnerable,

01:09:08.565 --> 01:09:14.530
so we, you know, are easy
to buy into anything, you know?

01:09:14.571 --> 01:09:17.532
[tense music]

01:09:17.574 --> 01:09:24.581
♪ ♪

01:09:43.559 --> 01:09:45.935
- Okay,
just hold this position.

01:09:45.978 --> 01:09:47.020
